hands_on_practices.solution:
1. Relevant equations:
$$F_2^p(x)=x\bigl(e_u^2\,u^p(x)+e_d^2\,d^p(x)\bigr),\quad
F_2^n(x)=x\bigl(e_u^2\,d^p(x)+e_d^2\,u^p(x)\bigr).$$
2. Define $R=\frac{d^p}{u^p}$, then
$$\frac{F_2^n}{F_2^p}
=\frac{e_u^2\,d^p+e_d^2\,u^p}{e_u^2\,u^p+e_d^2\,d^p}
=\frac{e_u^2 R+e_d^2}{e_u^2+e_d^2 R}.$$
3. Substitute $e_u^2=(2/3)^2=4/9$, $e_d^2=(-1/3)^2=1/9$, $R=1/5$:
$$\text{Numerator}= \frac{4}{9}\cdot\frac{1}{5}+\frac{1}{9}
=\frac{4}{45}+\frac{5}{45}=\frac{9}{45}=\frac{1}{5},$$
$$\text{Denominator}= \frac{4}{9}+\frac{1}{9}\cdot\frac{1}{5}
=\frac{20}{45}+\frac{1}{45}=\frac{21}{45}=\frac{7}{15}.$$
4. Thus
$$\lim_{x\to1}\frac{F_2^n}{F_2^p}
=\frac{\tfrac{1}{5}}{\tfrac{7}{15}}
=\frac{1}{5}\cdot\frac{15}{7}
=\frac{3}{7}.$$
